			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2024</a> paper:</span><br><i>Design of Software Representation Languages: A Historical Perspective</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnthonyIraWasserman.html">Anthony Ira Wasserman</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3687997.3695649">10.1145/3687997.3695649</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It discusses design choices and guidelines for notations and representation languages used to develop software.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The historical narrative connects language proliferation to long-term maintenance and legacy-system pressures.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2e.html"><span class="tagL">T2E: Documentation</span></a><ul><li> Representation notations are treated as artifacts that document programs and enable communication about software.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagL">T6D: Synergies</span></a><ul><li> As an SLEBoK-style essay, it synthesizes perspectives across communities and time periods.
</li></ul></li></ul>
